Since 1986, George Steinmetz has completed more than 40 major photo essays for National Geographic and 25 stories for GEO magazine in Germany, exploring the most remote str­etches of Arabia's Empty Quarter to the­ unknown tree people of Irian Jaya. His expeditions to the Sahara and Gobi deserts have been featured in separate "National Geographic Explorer" programs. In 2006 he was awarded a grant by the National Science Foundation to document the work of scientists in the Dry Valleys and volcanoes of Antarctica.

Steinmetz began his career in photography after hitchhiking through Africa for 28 months. He then spent fifteen years photographing all of the world’s extreme deserts while piloting a motorized paraglider. This experimental aircraft enables him to capture unique images of the world, inaccessible by traditional aircraft and most other modes of transportation. He has authored four books, and his current project is documenting the challenge of meeting humanity’s rapidly expanding demand for food.

title: Photos of Africa, taken from a flying lawn chair

aws-transcripts.transcript: I have to tell you, it's more than a little intimidating up here. An old American guy trying to tell African something new about your own continent. But sometimes an outsider conceived things in a different way, like from the air. That's when I found by flying low and slow all over the African continent as I photographed the spectacle of its diversity. And I wasn't always an old guy. This is me in 1979 a kid from California backpacking his way through the Atari force of the year. I was on a year long hitch hiking trip. I just dropped out of Stanford University on I went from Tunis to Kisangani into Cairo. I learned how to live on $10 a day. It was an amazing experience for me. I spent about a week in this stinking cattle camp on the banks of the Nile in south Sudan. The Dinka taught me how to fight the pirates into a shelter, and also I observed how they had had the adapted their way of life around the migratory needs of their beloved cattle. It was like a graduate course in ecological ethnography, and I got busy taking notes with a camera with no money for rides. They often made the Mizuguchi right on the roof of the trucks or, in this case, on the top of the train going across south Sudan. I felt like I was riding on the back of an insect going across the enormous tapestry of Africa. It was incredible view from up there, but I couldn't help but think, Wouldn't it be even more amazing if I could fly over that landscape like a bird? Well, that notion stay with me. And 20 years later, after confession photographer, I was able to talk National Geographic and doing a big story in the Central Sahara, and I came back with a new kind of flying machine. This is me Pilot World's lightest in slowest aircraft left, it's called a motorized paraglider. It consists of a backpack motor in a parachute style wing, and it flies about 30 miles an hour with 10 liters of fuel. I can fly for about two hours, but what's really amazing about it is it gives me a nun instructive you both horizontally and vertically, like a flying launch. Here. My hitchhikers, you were flying over after it came true when I spotted these two camel caravans passing out in the middle of Saharan. The one in the foreground is carrying salt out of the desert, while the one in the background is caring fodder for the animals. Heading back in, I realized that you couldn't take this kind of picture of the conventional aircraft. An airplane moves too fast. Helicopter be too loud with too much downdraft. And then it dawned on me that this this crazy it'll aircraft was flying would open up a new way of seeing remote parts of the African landscape in a way that never really been possible for Let me show you how it works. This may seem a bit dangerous, but I'm not some kind of adventure dude, I'm a photographer with flies, and I only fly to take pictures. My favorite altitude is between 205 100 feet, where I can see the world three dimensionally, but also at a human scale. I find that a lot of what I've done over the years in Africa you could probably you could try to do with the drone, but drones aren't really made for exploration. They only fly for about 20 minutes of battery life in about three kilometers of range, and I get to see if it's on a little screen in front of you. But I like to explore.
